DO  - https://doi.org/10.1006/jfin.1993.1002
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957383710028
AB  - This paper analyzes the effects of market value accounting (MVA) on loan maturity. I show that in the presence of asymmetric information MVA introduces a bias into asset valuation against longer-term illiquid assets. This bias increases interest rates for long-maturity loans and induces a shift to short-term self-liquidating loans. With the liquidity production of banks curtailed, borrowers may face "excessive" liquidation. The desirability of MVA applied to loans is thus questionable. Journal of Economic Literature Classification Numbers: G21, G28, M41.
